data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. In .NET 10, you could configure it as a temporary migration aid, but in .NET 11 (EF Core 11), synchronous operations on the Cosmos provider now throw `InvalidOperationException` unconditionally — there's no opt-in to re-enable them.

Every call in your repository is affected:

| Sync (breaks) | Async (replacement) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `ToListAsync()` |
| `First(...)` | `FirstAsync(...)` |
| `Count()` | `CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `SaveChangesAsync()` |

## Required migration

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `async Task<T>` return types replace synchronous returns
- All callers up the chain must also become `async`/`await` — this "colors" your call stack up to the controller
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's an in-memory tracking operation, not a DB call)
- Remove any `EnableSyncOverAsync` / `AllowSynchronousIO` Cosmos configuration — it's no longer recognized
